109 And I added to him: «And the death of your lineage»;
110 because of which, accumulating grief upon grief,
111 he went away like a sad and mad person.

112 But I remained to watch the troop,
113 and I saw something that I would be afraid,
114 without further proof, to recount alone;

118 I saw for sure, and it still seems to me that I see it,
119 a headless trunk walking just as
120 the others of the sad flock were walking;

124 It made a lantern of itself for itself,
125 and they were two in one and one in two;
126 how that can be, He knows who so ordains it.

